MUCH TO HIS DISMAY, his siblings were all girls, so they got to go home with mama.  I was quickly fostered into a great human family with other bunnies.  Unfortunately, the bonded group and I just were not meant to be.  I am about just about 20 weeks as I returned to RASKC on 26 July, a few days after I got fixed.  Human family made sure I was comfortable post procedure in an environment I loved.  Current Location: King County Pet Adoption Center 21615 64TH AVE S KENT, WA 98032<p/><p/>I tried hard to bond to the other rabbits during foster time. I was always nice and licked the girls.  The existing buck rabbit did not take kindly to me joining ranks.<p/>I did have some wonderful times running and playing with a couple of rabbits at foster, and I was very gentle, unless I accidentally jumped on someone by mistake.  Still grasping the whole rabbit airborne maneuvers.  Humans love to watch, and I love to show them my new moves.<p/><p/>So, in short, I feel I will not have any trouble bonding with another rabbit friend with proper introductions. If you are considering adding a second bunny to your family, familiarize yourself with the rabbit bonding process and don't hesitate to reach out if you would like us to host a speed date to find the best match.<p/><p/>When it comes to feeding me, I will need the proper balance of pellets, timothy hay, fresh vegetables and access to fresh water!  I am still growing and get excited for human contact and dinner time salad especially.  I may be a little awkward/clumsy right now, but I do give my human friends another reason to smile.  After dinner salad time I love to run around, jump, do binkies, and get pettings.  Did I say, I like to have cuddle time with humans when I am ready?<p/><p/>As a young bunny, I like to help in the kitchen and get the salads ready for all bunnies.  I love to check different salad components for freshness and flavor.  One of my top skills in the foster family was helping consume salad.  Another top skill was taking naps on top of my hidey house preparing for hard work in the kitchen at dinner time.<p/><p/>When it was my time to run around and explore the house, I remembered to return to my litter box.  Sometimes I would excel at too much exercise and just crash anywhere.  Lucky the house was mostly carpeted, so when I when plump, it just felt good and relaxing.<p/>
